d Kingdom","Creedy, Devon, England":"Devon, England","Crediton, Devon, England":"Crediton, Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Creedy","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["1  English: locative name from North Creedy in Sandford or Lower Creedy in Upton Hellions (Devon).","2  Scottish Gaelic: from  <b>Mac Riada</b>,  see  McCready  ."],"variants":[{"name":"McCready","meanings":["Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Riada</b> ‘son of <i>Riada</i>’, an old personal name meaning ‘traveler, rider’. The surname was found in Galloway, Scotland, in 1684, but it seems likely (with the variant <b>McGready</b>) to have originated in Ireland."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William John Creedy was born in 1321, in Devon, England, United Kingdom, his father, William Creedy, was 23 and his mother, Anne De Beaumont, was 22. He married Isabel Wake about 1350, in Devon, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at lea